---ARCHITECTURE---
project:            llmisland-mix-tooling
version:            0.3-rc8
last-verified:      2026-05-07
description:        Reference tooling for the LLM Island System.
                    A thin orchestrator (llmisland_tooling.py) dispatches
                    subcommands into the tooling/ package. Each subcommand
                    is its own module; standard library only.

propagation-status: idle
propagation-pending:
  - none

bootstrap-mode:     greenfield
bootstrap-date:     2026-05-03

scope:              tooling-only — the spec/docs portion of mix is NOT
                    islanded. Only the Python sources under tooling/ and
                    llmisland_tooling.py at the project root participate
                    in this mainland. See notes.md item 8 (locked).

layers:
  orchestration:    [llmisland_tooling.py]
  core:             [tooling/common.py, tooling/types.py]
  io:               [tooling/stale.py, tooling/spec_router.py,
                     tooling/rules.py, tooling/validate.py,
                     tooling/_validate_island.py, tooling/_validate_symbols.py,
                     tooling/_validate_mainland.py]
  data:             [tooling/propagation.py]
  config:           [tooling/_enums.py]
  test:             []
  config:           []
  build:            []
  bridge:           []

load-order:
  - tooling/types.py         :: dataclasses; imported by orchestrator + subcommands
  - tooling/common.py        :: helpers; loaded by every subcommand module
  - tooling/stale.py         :: registers check-stale, check-decay
  - tooling/spec_router.py   :: registers spec
  - tooling/propagation.py   :: registers prop-start, prop-done, prop-status, prop-finish
  - tooling/rules.py         :: registers validate-rules
  - tooling/_enums.py        :: enum sets / required-field lists
  - tooling/_validate_symbols.py    :: per-SYMBOL validation
  - tooling/_validate_island.py     :: per-island validation; imports
                                       _enums + _validate_symbols
  - tooling/_validate_mainland.py   :: mainland validation; imports
                                       _enums + parser helpers from
                                       _validate_island
  - tooling/validate.py      :: registers validate (orchestration shell)
  - tooling/__init__.py      :: package marker
  - llmisland_tooling.py     :: entrypoint; imports subcommand modules

architectural-rules:
  - AR-001: every subcommand lives in its own module under tooling/
    self-checkable: true
  - AR-002: every cmd_* function returns either an int exit code or
            a tooling.common.Report dataclass; the orchestrator
            handles all formatting
    self-checkable: true
  - AR-003: --json and --include-examples must be available on every
            subcommand via argparse parent parsers (no per-cmd
            duplication, no decorators)
    self-checkable: true
  - AR-004: zero external dependencies; standard library only.
            requirements.txt does not exist by design
    self-checkable: true
  - AR-005: each tooling/*.py file stays under 300 lines (CONTRIBUTING
            yellow line); split into helper modules if it grows past
    self-checkable: false (requires line-count check; future check-size tool)

---CONNECTIONS---

CONNECTION: llmisland_tooling.py -> tooling/types.py
  uses:         Report (dataclass returned by subcommands)
  why:          orchestrator's _emit dispatcher needs the Report type
                to format JSON or text output uniformly
  direction:    orchestration -> core
  strength:     critical
  break-impact: every subcommand's output formatting fails;
                --json mode produces invalid output
  cycle:        false

CONNECTION: tooling/stale.py -> tooling/common.py
  uses:         iter_islands, source_for_island, read_header_field,
                parse_last_verified, is_example_path
  why:          check-stale and check-decay walk every island and parse
                their last-verified / confidence-review-due fields
  direction:    io -> core
  strength:     critical
  break-impact: check-stale and check-decay both fail entirely
  cycle:        false

CONNECTION: tooling/stale.py -> tooling/types.py
  uses:         Finding, Report
  why:          subcommand handlers return Report; findings are Finding
  direction:    io -> core
  strength:     critical
  break-impact: handlers cannot construct return values; orchestrator
                dispatch breaks for both subcommands
  cycle:        false

CONNECTION: tooling/spec_router.py -> tooling/common.py
  uses:         find_project_root
  why:          spec --topic auto-detects the project root to find
                the SPEC/ directory when --spec-dir is not given
  direction:    io -> core
  strength:     high
  break-impact: spec --topic must be invoked from the project root
                or with --spec-dir; default-discovery breaks
  cycle:        false

CONNECTION: tooling/spec_router.py -> tooling/types.py
  uses:         Finding, Report
  why:          handler returns Report on errors / --json mode
  direction:    io -> core
  strength:     high
  break-impact: error and --json paths fail; the print-and-exit path
                still works (returns int)
  cycle:        false

CONNECTION: llmisland_tooling.py -> tooling/stale.py
  uses:         SUBCOMMANDS dict
  why:          orchestrator iterates SUBCOMMAND_MODULES at parser-build
                time and registers each entry's parser + handler
  direction:    orchestration -> io
  strength:     critical
  break-impact: check-stale and check-decay are not registered; running
                them produces "Unknown subcommand"
  cycle:        false

CONNECTION: llmisland_tooling.py -> tooling/spec_router.py
  uses:         SUBCOMMANDS dict
  why:          same as above, for spec
  direction:    orchestration -> io
  strength:     critical
  break-impact: spec is not registered
  cycle:        false

CONNECTION: llmisland_tooling.py -> tooling/propagation.py
  uses:         SUBCOMMANDS dict
  why:          same as above, for prop-start, prop-done, prop-status, prop-finish
  direction:    orchestration -> data
  strength:     critical
  break-impact: cascade lifecycle commands are not registered;
                propagation cascades cannot be started or resumed
                via the tool, only via manual .llmpropstts edits
  cycle:        false

CONNECTION: llmisland_tooling.py -> tooling/rules.py
  uses:         SUBCOMMANDS dict
  why:          same as above, for validate-rules
  direction:    orchestration -> io
  strength:     high
  break-impact: validate-rules is not registered; LLM-assisted
                compliance review (RULE 9) loses its surfacing tool
  cycle:        false

CONNECTION: tooling/propagation.py -> tooling/common.py
  uses:         find_project_root
  why:          all four prop-* commands operate on .llmpropstts at
                the project root; find_project_root locates it
  direction:    data -> core
  strength:     critical
  break-impact: cascade commands cannot find the right project root;
                may operate on the wrong .llmpropstts in nested checkouts
  cycle:        false

CONNECTION: tooling/propagation.py -> tooling/types.py
  uses:         Finding, Report
  why:          handlers return Report; findings are Finding
  direction:    data -> core
  strength:     critical
  break-impact: handlers cannot construct return values; orchestrator
                dispatch breaks for all four prop-* commands
  cycle:        false

CONNECTION: tooling/propagation.py -> .llmpropstts
  uses:         on-disk format (status / started / origin / pending / completed)
  why:          this module is the canonical reader/writer of the
                cascade state file; the format is shared with manual
                fallback documented in SPEC/07_PROPAGATION.md
  direction:    data -> (external — runtime state file at project root)
  strength:     critical
  break-impact: cascade state corruption; manual fallback breaks if
                the format diverges from what SPEC/07 documents
  cycle:        false
  dynamic:      true
  dynamic-note: the .llmpropstts file is created and deleted at runtime;
                its presence itself signals "cascade in progress". The
                connection is declared so future LLM sessions know the
                shared on-disk contract is load-bearing.

CONNECTION: tooling/rules.py -> tooling/common.py
  uses:         MAINLAND_NAME, find_project_root
  why:          rules locates the mainland by walking up from cwd
                when --mainland is not given
  direction:    io -> core
  strength:     high
  break-impact: validate-rules without --mainland cannot find the
                mainland; --mainland fallback still works
  cycle:        false

CONNECTION: tooling/rules.py -> tooling/types.py
  uses:         Finding, Report
  why:          handler returns Report; per-rule entries are Finding
  direction:    io -> core
  strength:     critical
  break-impact: handler cannot construct return values
  cycle:        false

CONNECTION: llmisland_tooling.py -> tooling/validate.py
  uses:         SUBCOMMANDS dict
  why:          orchestrator iterates SUBCOMMAND_MODULES at parser-build
                time and registers each entry's parser + handler
  direction:    orchestration -> io
  strength:     critical
  break-impact: validate is not registered; the format validator
                (the deepest checker in the suite) becomes inaccessible
  cycle:        false

CONNECTION: tooling/validate.py -> tooling/_validate_island.py
  uses:         validate_island
  why:          validate.py is the orchestration shell; per-island
                validation lives in _validate_island.py (split rc8)
  direction:    io -> io
  strength:     critical
  break-impact: cmd_validate cannot validate any island
  cycle:        false

CONNECTION: tooling/validate.py -> tooling/_validate_mainland.py
  uses:         validate_mainland
  why:          mainland-specific checks live there
  direction:    io -> io
  strength:     critical
  break-impact: cmd_validate cannot validate the mainland
  cycle:        false

CONNECTION: tooling/_validate_island.py -> tooling/_enums.py
  uses:         BOOL_ENUM, CONFIDENCE_ENUM, LAYER_ENUM,
                MAINTAINED_BY_ENUM, READ_REASON_ENUM,
                REQUIRED_HEADER_FIELDS, REQUIRED_ISLAND_SECTIONS,
                REQUIRED_RISK_CATEGORIES, SEVERITY_ENUM, STATUS_ENUM
  why:          enum-checking + required-field iteration
  direction:    io -> config
  strength:     critical
  break-impact: per-island validation cannot enum-check anything
  cycle:        false

CONNECTION: tooling/_validate_island.py -> tooling/_validate_symbols.py
  uses:         iter_symbol_blocks, validate_one_symbol
  why:          per-SYMBOL validation lives in _validate_symbols.py
                (extracted in rc8 to keep _validate_island under the
                file-size red line)
  direction:    io -> io
  strength:     critical
  break-impact: SYMBOLS section validation skipped
  cycle:        false

CONNECTION: tooling/_validate_symbols.py -> tooling/_enums.py
  uses:         BOOL_ENUM, FRAGILITY_ENUM, SYMBOL_KIND_ENUM
  why:          enum-checking inside SYMBOL entries
  direction:    io -> config
  strength:     critical
  break-impact: SYMBOL enum checks fail
  cycle:        false

CONNECTION: tooling/_validate_mainland.py -> tooling/_enums.py
  uses:         BOOTSTRAP_MODE_ENUM, REQUIRED_ARCHITECTURE_FIELDS,
                REQUIRED_MAINLAND_SECTIONS
  why:          mainland enum-checks + required-section/field iteration
  direction:    io -> config
  strength:     critical
  break-impact: mainland validation cannot enum-check
  cycle:        false

CONNECTION: tooling/_validate_mainland.py -> tooling/_validate_island.py
  uses:         block_for, enum_token, find_kv, section_lines (parser
                helpers shared between island and mainland validation)
  why:          parser helpers live with island validation; mainland
                imports them rather than duplicating
  direction:    io -> io
  strength:     critical
  break-impact: mainland cannot parse sections
  cycle:        false

CONNECTION: tooling/_validate_island.py -> tooling/common.py
  uses:         is_example_path, parse_last_verified, source_for_island
  why:          per-island validation needs source-companion lookup
                and date parsing
  direction:    io -> core
  strength:     critical
  break-impact: per-island validation cannot resolve source files
                or parse last-verified
  cycle:        false

CONNECTION: tooling/_validate_mainland.py -> tooling/common.py
  uses:         MAINLAND_NAME
  why:          locate the mainland file at the project root
  direction:    io -> core
  strength:     high
  break-impact: mainland file cannot be located
  cycle:        false

CONNECTION: tooling/validate.py -> tooling/common.py
  uses:         iter_islands
  why:          orchestration shell walks islands once for the validator
  direction:    io -> core
  strength:     critical
  break-impact: validate cannot enumerate islands
  cycle:        false

CONNECTION: tooling/validate.py -> tooling/types.py
  uses:         Finding, Report
  why:          handler returns Report; aggregated findings are Finding
  direction:    io -> core
  strength:     critical
  break-impact: handler cannot construct return values
  cycle:        false

CONNECTION: tooling/_validate_island.py -> tooling/types.py
  uses:         Finding
  why:          per-island helpers emit Findings
  direction:    io -> core
  strength:     critical
  break-impact: validation findings cannot be constructed
  cycle:        false

CONNECTION: tooling/_validate_symbols.py -> tooling/types.py
  uses:         Finding
  why:          per-SYMBOL helpers emit Findings
  direction:    io -> core
  strength:     critical
  break-impact: SYMBOL validation findings cannot be constructed
  cycle:        false

CONNECTION: tooling/_validate_mainland.py -> tooling/types.py
  uses:         Finding
  why:          mainland helpers emit Findings
  direction:    io -> core
  strength:     critical
  break-impact: mainland validation findings cannot be constructed
  cycle:        false

CONNECTION: tooling/validate.py -> all .llmisland files
  uses:         the full island file format (sections, fields, enums)
  why:          validate parses every island as input
  direction:    io -> (external — every islanded file in the project)
  strength:     critical
  break-impact: validate produces false-positive errors when format
                conventions diverge from what the validator expects
  cycle:        false
  dynamic:      true
  dynamic-note: islanded files are themselves the input; the set is
                discovered at runtime via iter_islands. validate's job
                IS reading them, so this connection is core to its
                purpose, not a side effect.

CONNECTION: tooling/validate.py -> connections.llmainland
  uses:         the mainland file format (architecture fields, layer
                lists, CONNECTION endpoints, bootstrap-mode enum)
  why:          validate_mainland parses the mainland for architecture
                checks and verifies CONNECTION endpoints reference real
                islands
  direction:    io -> (external — the mainland itself, this very file)
  strength:     high
  break-impact: mainland-side validation breaks; islands still get
                checked
  cycle:        true
  cycle-note:   this mainland describes a tool that reads this very
                mainland — same shape as the rules.py cycle below.
                Honest declaration; harmless.

CONNECTION: tooling/rules.py -> connections.llmainland
  uses:         architectural-rules block; self-checkable sub-field
  why:          extracts rules grouped by self-checkable: true | false
                for LLM-assisted RULE 9 review
  direction:    io -> (external — the mainland itself, this very file)
  strength:     high
  break-impact: validate-rules returns no-rules when the mainland's
                architectural-rules block format diverges from what
                the regex expects
  cycle:        true
  cycle-note:   this mainland describes a tool that reads this very
                mainland. The cycle is real but harmless: the tool
                fails gracefully (no-rules warning) when its parse
                fails, and the mainland's format is constrained by
                SPEC/04_MAINLAND.md regardless of what this tool does.

CONNECTION: tooling/spec_router.py -> SPEC/
  uses:         every SPEC/NN_*.md file (read content for --topic
                resolution)
  why:          spec --topic returns the content of the matching SPEC
                module
  direction:    io -> (external — the spec docs themselves)
  strength:     high
  break-impact: spec --topic returns spec-file-missing for renamed
                or removed SPEC modules
  cycle:        false
  dynamic:      true
  dynamic-note: SPEC files are markdown documentation, not code with
                its own islands (per locked decision in notes.md item
                8: spec docs are not islanded). The connection is
                declared here because spec_router.py reads the files
                at runtime — that runtime dependency matters even
                though the target side has no island.

---CONTRACTS---

CONTRACT: subcommand-return-shape
  statement:    every cmd_* returns either an int exit code or a
                tooling.common.Report dataclass. No subcommand may
                return a bare dict or define its own result type.
  owned-by:     llmisland_tooling.py (dispatcher enforces at runtime)
  enforced-by:  none yet — manual review until validate.py (rc8) lands
  islands-bound:[llmisland_tooling.py, tooling/common.py]
  violation-consequence: dispatcher cannot uniformly format output;
                         silent breakage of --json output mode for
                         the offending subcommand
  fragility:    high (rationale: not enforced by Python's type system;
                                  trivial to violate by returning a
                                  bare dict)

CONTRACT: zero-dependency
  statement:    every import in tooling/ and llmisland_tooling.py
                resolves to the Python 3.10+ standard library.
                requirements.txt MUST NOT be created.
  owned-by:     project root
  enforced-by:  none yet — manual review
  islands-bound:[llmisland_tooling.py, tooling/common.py]
  violation-consequence: adopters who installed mix without pip cannot
                         run the tools; zero-friction install promise
                         broken
  fragility:    high (rationale: easy to import a third-party module
                                  by reflex; no boundary in code to
                                  catch it)

CONTRACT: shared-flags-via-parent
  statement:    --json and --include-examples are added once on the
                shared parent parser in build_parser. Subcommands
                attach via parents=[common]. Subcommands MUST NOT
                redefine these flags.
  owned-by:     llmisland_tooling.py (build_parser)
  enforced-by:  none yet — manual review
  islands-bound:[llmisland_tooling.py]
  violation-consequence: argparse argument-conflict error at startup;
                         OR (worse) silent override of dispatcher's
                         flag handling
  fragility:    medium (rationale: argparse fails loudly on
                                    conflict-add, so a violation is
                                    detectable; less fragile than the
                                    return-shape contract)

---ARCHITECTURE-MEMORY---

ACTIVE-CONSTRAINTS:
  - id: MAC-001
    constraint:  the orchestrator must not duplicate logic from
                 tooling/ modules — its only job is parser
                 construction and dispatch
    applies-to:  [llmisland_tooling.py]
    established: 2026-05-03
    evidence:    inferred-from-design (HD-001)

  - id: MAC-002
    constraint:  the spec docs (LLMISLAND_SPEC.md, SPEC/*, README.md,
                 etc.) are NOT islanded and do not appear in this
                 mainland. Only the Python tooling layer is in scope.
    applies-to:  [project root]
    established: 2026-05-03
    evidence:    inferred-from-notes.md (locked decision item 8)

HISTORICAL-DECISIONS:
  - id: MHD-001
    decision:  hybrid orchestrator + package, not single-file CLI
    reason:    file-size rule (~200 / ~300 / 400+) pushed toward a
               package; an LLM working on the tools wants one
               entrypoint so it does not have to navigate to find
               the right file. Hybrid satisfies both: thin
               orchestrator (one name to remember) + small modules
               (each under the size limit).
    date:      2026-04-27
    outcome:   in use as of v0.3-rc5; first rc with code in this layout
    evidence:  inferred-from-notes.md

  - id: MHD-002
    decision:  argparse parent parsers for --json, not decorators
    reason:    the tooling will be maintained by an LLM. Parent
               parsers are a pattern every LLM has seen thousands of
               times in its training corpus; custom decorator stacks
               for CLI flag inheritance are not. When two designs
               are functionally equivalent, the LLM-recognizable one
               wins. (Meta-principle from notes.md.)
    date:      2026-04-27
    outcome:   in use as of v0.3-rc5
    evidence:  inferred-from-tooling questions responses.md

  - id: MHD-003
    decision:  bootstrap-mode greenfield (not legacy)
    reason:    the tooling layer is authored fresh with islands from
               day one — that matches the greenfield definition.
               The spec/docs portion of mix predates this work, but
               this mainland's scope is the tooling layer only.
    date:      2026-05-03
    outcome:   stable; first islands in mix are tooling-side
    evidence:  inferred-from-notes.md

  - id: MHD-004
    decision:  propagation state in a separate .llmpropstts file,
               NOT in this mainland
    reason:    transient operational state should not pollute the
               architectural document. The mainland describes intent;
               .llmpropstts describes operations in flight. Auto-
               deletes when a cascade completes, so its presence
               itself is a strong honest signal.
    date:      2026-04-27
    outcome:   propagation-status field stays at "idle"; tooling/
               propagation.py (rc7) manages the .llmpropstts file
    evidence:  inferred-from-tooling questions responses.md

  - id: MHD-006
    decision:  this mainland file is exempt from the project's
               400-line file-size rule
    reason:    SPEC/04_MAINLAND.md explicitly forbids splitting the
               mainland into a .history file or any other partition.
               The selective read protocol (SPEC/04 + LLM_BOOT.md
               STEP 1) is the alternative — readers never load the
               full mainland anyway. Its size scales with the
               number of source files in scope; growth past 400 is
               an architectural fact, not a rule violation. The
               file-size rule in CONTRIBUTING.md applies to spec
               modules and tooling source; the mainland is governed
               by SPEC/04 instead.
    date:      2026-05-07
    outcome:   stable; the mainland will continue to grow as the
               tooling layer grows. If it ever becomes a real reading
               problem, the answer is to introduce workspace.llmainland
               for monorepo splits (SPEC/10), not to fragment a single
               project's mainland.
    evidence:  SPEC/04_MAINLAND.md "NOTE ON SPLITTING THE MAINLAND"

  - id: MHD-005
    decision:  v0.3 ships 8 subcommands; remaining tooling ideas are
               recorded as deferred backlog, not built
    reason:    fork roadmaps (codex tooling_idea + antigravity
               tooling_idea_antigravity, both retained outside mix as
               historical artifacts) listed several more tools. Each
               was evaluated against the rule "if the tool would need
               to invent policy, the policy is not ready." The
               following are deferred to a post-v0.3 release:
               - File Edit Hook (auto-mark maintained-by:
                 human-unreviewed on git pre-commit) — depends on a
                 git/editor integration story we have not designed.
                 Antigravity flagged this as "too heavy for now."
               - Human Island Editor (structured form for human edits
                 enforcing required fields) — useful but requires UI
                 design that does not fit the LLM-driven scope yet.
               - Security Integrity Checker (tamper-evident hashes for
                 high-severity islands) — depends on a signing scheme
                 we have not picked. SPEC/11_SECURITY.md acknowledges
                 the surface; the tool can wait.
               - Mainland Slicer (output a task-specific subset of
                 the mainland) — selective read protocol in
                 SPEC/04_MAINLAND.md addresses the underlying problem
                 by prompting; tooling extension is later optimization.
               - Subjective Field Linter (reject confidence/fragility
                 above low without rationale) — partially covered by
                 validate.py's _enum_token + RULE 8 awareness; full
                 rationale-quality check needs semantic judgment a
                 tool cannot provide.
    date:      2026-05-07
    outcome:   v0.3 ships 8 subcommands. Backlog above carries
               forward; each item gets re-evaluated when its
               prerequisite (UI design, signing scheme, etc.) is ready.
    evidence:  inferred-from-tooling_idea (fork-side files retained
               as historical artifacts at LLMISLAND - codex/ and
               LLMISLAND - antigravity/; not present in mix)

SUPERSEDED:
  - none yet
